{{Infobox company | name = Stemettes | native_name = | native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. "fr" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. --> | logo = File:Stemettes Logo.png | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | logo_padding = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = | type = | founded = 2013 | founders = [[Anne-Marie Imafidon]] and [[Jacquelyn Guderley]] | hq_location_city = [[London]] | hq_location_country = [[United Kingdom]] | industry = [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] | products = [http://www.outboxincubator.com Outbox Incubator], [http://www.studenttostemette.org Student to Stemette], [http://www.ototheb.com OtotheB] | website = [http://www.stemettes.org stemettes.org] }}
'''Stemettes''' is a [[social enterprise]] which encourages girls aged between 5–22 years old to pursue careers in Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths, or [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]]. Stemettes runs panel events, [[hackathon]]s, the Student to Stemette mentoring programme supported by [[Deutsche Bank]], Outbox Incubator and an app, OtotheB, an online platform for girls interested in STEM and [[entrepreneurship]].
==History== Stemettes was started in 2013 by British mathematics and computing child prodigy [[Anne-Marie Imafidon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Lydia|title=Women in Science: Meet the Stemettes star inspiring more girls into STEM|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/women-science-meet-stemettes-star-inspiring-more-girls-into-stem-1543094|accessdate=23 August 2016|date=11 February 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Jacquelyn Guderley became co-founder of Stemettes alongside Imafidon.{{clarify|reason=makes no sense - if she joined 2 years after it was started then she cannot be co-founder|date=December 2017}}
Stemettes has partnered with organisations including [[Deutsche Bank]], [[Salesforce]], [[Accenture]], [[Bank of America Merrill Lynch]], [[BP]] and [[Microsoft]]. The organisation is regularly called upon by the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] and [[European Commission]] to consult on matters related to women in STEM.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
==Outbox Incubator== For six weeks from July–August 2015, Stemettes ran Outbox Incubator in London. This residential business incubator for girls with STEM start-ups became known as the “X-men house for girls”<ref>Ravanona, Anna. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/anne-ravanona/inside-outbox-incubator-m_b_8423472.html Inside Outbox Incubator: Meet the Startups Built By Girls in STEM - Part 1], [[The Huffington Post]], 29 April 2015.</ref>
In February 2016, the Outbox Incubator spin-off app, OtotheB, was officially launched. The app is an online platform for girls interested in STEM and entrepreneurship. The app has been well received by some STEM figures such as academic and campaigner [[Sue Black (computer scientist)|Sue Black]], who described the app as a “…fantastic new resource for young women interested in technology”.<ref>Armstrong, John. [http://irishtechnews.net/ITN3/stemettes-launch-ototheb-app-to-inspire-girls-into-stem-careers Stemettes launch OtotheB app to inspire girls into STEM careers],[http://irishtechnews.net/ITN3/ Irish Tech News], 11 February 2016.</ref>
==Awards and recognition== Stemettes was named as European Digital Impact Organisation of the Year in October 2014 <ref>[http://digitalimpactaward.com/2014/11/01/2014-european-digital-impact-organisation 2014 European Digital Impact Organisation],[http://dlii.org/ Digital Leadership Institute]. Retrieved 20 April 2016.</ref> by the Digital Leadership Institute.
